      "type": "edit",
      "id": "4b5389de-9ea1-49e2-8be0-216468d9d66d",
      "item": {
        "id": "4b5389de-9ea1-49e2-8be0-216468d9d66d",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "The more commonly spoken languages dominate the less commonly spoken languages, so the less commonly spoken languages eventually disappear from populations. The total number of languages in the world is not known. Estimates vary depending on many factors. The consensus is that there are between 6,000 and 7,000 languages spoken as of 2010, and that between 50–90% of those will have become extinct by the year 2100. The top 20 languages ([[List of languages by number of native speakers]]), those spoken by more than 50 million speakers each, are spoken by 50% of the world's population, whereas many of the other languages are spoken by small communities, most of them with less than 10,000 speakers.<ref name=\"Handbook\"/>"
      },
